                     <interp inst="t18320906-255-person2075" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the prosecutor's wife. I received five soverereigns and a half, two half-crowns, and five shillings, which I put into a small box, and placed on the kitchen mantel-piece, in the prisoner's presence; he wrote a receipt for it for me, and I left him in the kitchen, writing a letter for himself; I returned in about ten minutes - he was gone; the box was in its place, but the money gone from it; we could hear nothing of the prisoner.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-255-person2076">
                  GEORGE 
                  DEHANE
               <interp inst="t18320906-255-person2076" type="surname" value="DEHANE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-255-person2076" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-255-person2076" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Policeman. On the 9th of August I was in New North-road; the prisoner came to me - he said he had committed a robbery, and wished to be taken into custody, for he had been at Bristol, and he could get nothing to do, and would rather be transported than remain in England - he said he was sorry for what he had done; that he had robbed Mr. Harding - he told me the amount, and when he had done it.</p>
